            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ava Rostami is a product of two worlds: her father, a pragmatic Iranian engineer who fled Tehran just before the revolution, and her mother, a thoughtful librarian from Ohio. Raised in Berkeley, Ava\u2019s childhood was a blend of her father\u2019s emphasis on logic and ambition and her mother\u2019s love for literature and quiet contemplation. This duality shaped a fiercely intelligent and deeply reflective young woman.\n\nHer initial path led her to UCLA for a biology degree, driven by a fascination with the intricate systems of life. However, during a lab internship, she had a critical realization: she was more energized by the strategy of scientific discovery\u2014the funding, market positioning, and corporate chess\u2014than the painstaking work at the bench. This turning point led her to pursue an MBA at UC Berkeley's Haas School of Business, where she found her true calling at the intersection of science and commerce.\n\nAva\u2019s career in life sciences consulting was a steep, successful climb. Her twenties and thirties were a blur of long hours, complex projects, and international travel. Her relentless drive propelled her up the ladder, but it came at a personal cost; a marriage to a fellow ambitious professional dissolved in her late thirties, buckling under the weight of two demanding careers. The divorce was a painful but clarifying event, forcing Ava to redefine success on her own terms.\n\nNow 51, Ava has curated a life of intentionality in her chic Hayes Valley condo. Her mornings begin with yoga before she takes the Muni 2.3 miles to her Financial District office. As Director of Strategy, her days are a whirlwind of high-stakes decisions, shaping the future of pharmaceutical and biotech companies. Evenings are for herself: a run along the Embarcadero, a new play downtown, or intimate dinners with a small, trusted circle of friends, many of whom she\u2019s known for decades.\n\nSan Francisco is both her professional stage and her personal sanctuary. She loves the city\u2019s intellectual energy and culinary scene but is acutely aware of its fractures. Her ambitions have softened, shifting from climbing higher to building a legacy. Ava dreams of one day pivoting her expertise toward a non-profit, perhaps a foundation focused on global health equity, mentoring the next generation of women in a field she helped shape. She seeks a final act that is less about profit margins and more about purpose."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was 21, in a sterile UCLA lab surrounded by the hum of centrifuges. While waiting for a culture to incubate, she idly read a press release about a rival biotech firm securing a massive funding round. A jolt, more electric than any successful experiment, shot through her. The strategy, the risk, the victory\u2014it was a language she understood instinctively. In that moment, the tedious precision of lab work faded. She didn't want to just discover the molecule; she wanted to build the empire that brought it to the world.\n\n***\n\n2.\nThe end of her marriage wasn\u2019t a dramatic fight but a quiet conversation in their sleek South Beach condo. It was just after her 38th birthday. They sat across from each other, two exhausted CEOs of their own lives, realizing they\u2019d optimized everything except their connection. \"We\u2019re more like a merger that failed to create synergy,\" he\u2019d said, with a sad, pragmatic finality she recognized in herself. The grief was immense, but beneath it lay a sliver of relief\u2014the freedom to finally define success on her own, singular terms.\n\n***\n\n3.\nOne Saturday morning in her early forties, she was wandering through the Ferry Building Farmers Market. The sharp, floral scent of saffron from a vendor\u2019s display stopped her cold. Suddenly, she was a child in her Berkeley kitchen, watching her father meticulously grind spices for a stew while explaining the physics of bridge construction. It was a potent memory of his two worlds\u2014engineering and Iran\u2014coexisting. That scent reaffirmed the same duality in herself, a comforting anchor after the storm of her divorce.\n\n***\n\n4.\nIt was late on a Tuesday, she was 49. A brilliant but anxious young analyst was in her office, nearly in tears over a flaw in a strategic model. The old Ava would have been ruthless. Instead, she found herself sharing a story of a major mistake from her own early career. A surprising warmth bloomed in her chest\u2014not ambition, but a deep, protective empathy. It was a profound shift. Her legacy wouldn't be a series of successful projects, but the wisdom she could pass on to the women following in her path.\n\n***\n\n5.\nAfter a brutal day of negotiations, she went for a run. Pounding the pavement along the Embarcadero as dusk settled, the Bay Bridge began its nightly performance of sparkling lights. Her lungs burned and her mind, for the first time all day, was quiet. It was just the rhythm of her feet, the cool bay air, and the city\u2019s vast, unjudging beauty laid out before her. This was the peace she\u2019d earned. Not a conquest, but a sanctuary she had built for herself, one intentional step at a time."
